definition.value: A kidney AE that is characterized by a disease that causes abnormal blood clots to form in small blood vessels in the kidneys.
A urinary tract infection AE that is characterized by a type of urinary tract infection caused by bacteria where one or both kidneys become infected.

A urinary system AE that is characterized by the presence of bacteria in urine. It is often accompanied by symptoms is a urinary tract infection while that without is known as asymptomatic bacteriuria.
A bladder neoplasm AE that is characterized by a non-cancerous tumor of the bladder that does not spread (metastasize) to other parts of the body.
A bladder cancer AE that is characterized by cancer that has returned following initial treatment with surgery, radiation, chemotherapy, and immunotherapy.

A bladder AE that is characterized by problems with urination. This may include urgency of urination, frequency of urination, ability to "hold" urine during day or night, urinary incontinence, infrequent voiding, constipation, or other diagnoses.
A bladder AE that is characterized by a blockage at the base or neck of the bladder. Such a blockage reduces or stops the flow of urine into the urethra, which carries urine from the body.
A bladder AE that is characterized by a narrowing that can cause bladder obstruction that leads to incomplete bladder emptying.
A bladder cancer AE that is characterized by cancer that starts in the urothelial cells that line the inside of the bladder. It is the most common type of bladder cancer.
A urinary system AE that is characterized by yeast in the urine which can range from procurement contamination to a sign of a life-threatening, opportunistic fungal infection.
A bladder AE that is characterized by a severe and long-standing reduction in bladder capacity.

A kidney AE that is characterized by a medical test in which pain is elicited by percussion of the area of the back overlying the kidney (the costovertebral angle, an angle made by the vertebral column and the costal margin).
A kidney AE that is characterized by a major shock and renal failure after a crushing injury to skeletal muscle.

A urinary system AE thta is characterized by cloudy urine when the cause of cloudiness is due to crystals found in the urine when performing a urine test. It is considered often as a benign condition.

A cystitis AE that is characterized by a strong, persistent urge to urinate; a burning sensation when urinating; passing ferquent, small amounts of urine; blood in the urine (hematuria); passing cloudy or strong-smelling urine; pelvic discomfort; a feeling of pressure in the lower abdomen; and a low-grade fever.
A kidney AE that is characterized by a birth defect in which a kidney is located below, above, or on the opposite side of its usual position; about one in 900 people has an ectopic kidney.
A kidney AE that is characterized by two ureters coming from a single kidney.
A kidney AE that is characterized by a mixed bag of developmental abberations, all of which involve anatomical or major structural anomalies.
A kidney AE that is characterized by either partial or complete fusion of the two kidneys.

A urinary system AE that is characterized by either an anterior or posterior situation; the second type is the most common obstructive congenital malformation of the urethra. The condition presents with abnormal posterior urethral folds or membranes that prevent urine evacuation from the bladder.
A bladder AE that is characterized by the urodynamic description of bladder outlet obstruction from detrusor muscle contraction with concomitant involuntary urethral sphincter activation.

label.value: diabetic end stage renal disease AE

definition.value: A kidney AE that is characterized by the most advanced stage of kidney disease.
A kidney AE that is characterized by a serious kidney-related complication of type 1 diabetes and type 2 diabetes.
A kidney AE that is characterized by a rare disease that attacks the kidney's filtering units (glomeruli) causing serious scarring which leads to permanent kidney damage and even failure.
A urinary system AE that is characterized by urinary retention in young women; the problem is caused by the sphincter's failure to relax to allow urine to be passed.
A urinary system AE that is characterized by any symptom related to the urinary and genital organs.

A kidney AE that is characterized by inflammation and subsequent damage of the glomeruli leading to hematuria, proteinuria, and azotemia; it may be caused by primary renal disease or systemic conditions. Acute glomerulonephritis is the third most common cause of end-stage renal disease.
A kidney AE that is characterized by glomerulonephritis that develops silently (without symptoms) over several years, leading, often, to complete kidney failure.
A kidney AE that is characterized by a type of glomerulonephritis caused by deposits in the kidney glomerular mesangium and basement membrane thickening.
A kidney AE that is characterized by a specific type of glomerulonephritis that develops when inflammation of your kidney structures causes problems with the functioning of your kidney.
A kidney AE that is characterized by a disease affecting the kidneys which causes a nephrotic syndrome.
A kidney AE that is characterized by an increased number of cells in the glomerulus.
A kidney AE that is characterized by any disease of renal glomeruli.

An autoimmune disorder AE that is characterized by a rare autoimmune disease in which antibodies attack the basement membrane in lungs and kidneys, leading to bleeding from the lungs and kidney failure.
A urinary system AE that is characterized by bleeding of the urinary tract that can happen without a clear cause or as a result of an injury.
A kidney AE that is characterized by a rare kidney disease leading to chronic kidney disease in a non-negligible percentage of patients.

A urinary system AE that is characterized by when hemoglobin is released from RBCs into the bloodstream in excess of the binding capacity of haptoglobin. It occurs with chronic introvascular hemolysis and is called "brown urine."
A kidney AE that is characterized by rapid deterioration in kidney function in individuals with cirrhosis or fulminant liver failure. It is a life-threatening medical condition.
A urinary system AE that is characterized by an excessive urinary excretion of oxalate.
A nephropathy AE that is characterized by a disease of the kidneys where the vasculature of the kidneys is damaged with an increase in blood pressure (high blood pressure).
A urinary system AE that is characterized by low urinary-citrate excretion (defined as less than 320 mg/day), which can cause kidney stones in up to 2/3 of cases.
A congenital AE that is characterized by a congenital disorder of the urethra where the urinary opening is not at the usual location on the head of the penis.
A bladder AE that is characterized by the hypotonic bladder muscle failing to squeeze hard enough to completely empty the bladder.
An AE with the fragmentation of the nucleus

A cardiac disorder AE that shows a disorder of the heart's electrical activity, which can cause sudden, uncontrollable, dangerous arrhythmias in response to exercise or stress. The term "long QT" refers to an abnormal pattern seen on an EKG (electrocardiogram), a test that detects and records the heart's electrical activity.
an injection-site AE that displays erythema at the injection site.
an adverse event that occurs immediately after an injection
an adverse event that displays swelling at the injection site
